<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
NO DEAL: 3 PADRES FOR DALE MURPHY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Any chance Braves slugger Dale Murphy would be traded to San Diego has been 
killed by Atlanta General Manager Bobby Cox, who decided the available Padres 
players are "not what we're looking for." Cox made the decision after reviewing 
a report by Braves scout Wes Westrum, who spent the past week evaluating Padres 
talent at San Diego's spring training camp in Yuma. Although Cox declined to be 
specific, the report apparently singled out catcher Sandy Alomar Jr., pitcher 
Greg Harris and outfielder John Kruk as the top three Padres trade prospects. 
But Cox decided they weren't enough to pry Murphy loose from Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
Padres Manager Jack McKeon said his optimism about the potential deal waned as 
the talks that began in December bogged down in recent weeks. He downplayed the 
significance of the breakdown in discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
